INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,1,1,'und',0,'Anbieterkennzeichung nach §6 Teledienstgesetz (information provider identification according to §6 Teledienstgesetz) :\r\n\r\n\r\nBeVolunteer\r\nc/o Jean-Yves Hegron\r\n19 rue de Paris\r\n35500 Vitre\r\nFrance\r\n\r\n: info@bevolunteer.org\r\nBeWelcome is the property of the BeVolunteer non profit organization (see BeVolunteer Wiki)\r\n\r\n((The layout is based on YAML © 2005-2006 by Dirk Jesse))','','filtered_html'),('node','page',0,2,2,'und',0,'Trips\r\nCreate trips and see where other travellers are heading.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"/blog\">Blogs</a>\r\nCreate your own blog posts, surf lots of other member blogs.\r\n\r\nChat -> http://drupal.org/project/chatroom - <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/904006\">waiting for D7 version</a>\r\nTalk to the crowd, live on the ajax chat.\r\n\r\nShop -> http://drupal.org/project/spreadshirt - module inactive\r\nLooking for a present or souvenirs? Get nice items with BeWelcome logo in the shop!\r\n\r\nGallery\r\nUpload your pictures, create albums and integrate them in your blog and your profile.\r\nhttp://drupal.org/project/views_gallery is a good solution - http://drupal.org/node/651114\r\n\r\nForum\r\nGet the latest information and discuss travel plans with other members.\r\n\r\nGroups\r\nFind or create groups to share your ideas with likeminded people.\r\n* og open D7 issues: http://drupal.org/project/issues/og?text=&status=Open&priorities=All&categories=All&version=7.x&component=All\r\n\r\nWiki\r\nAdd, edit or correct wiki pages. It is your BeWelcome wiki. Please help us to extend the content.\r\n* for now: <a href=\"http://couchwiki.org/\">couchwiki</a>\r\n','','filtered_html'),('node','page',0,3,3,'und',0,'<h2>Meet locals worldwide</h2> \r\nBeWelcome is a culture crossing network that lets you share a place to sleep, meet up and help others on their way. Let us show you how!\r\n\r\nThis is a test site for porting BeWelcome to Drupal.\r\nSee also http://couchwiki.org/en/Migrating_BeWelcome_to_Drupal','','full_html'),('node','blog',0,4,4,'und',0,'Moving from user fields to <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/profile2\">profile2</a>. Several reasons:\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Exportable into Features</li>\r\n<li>Separation between my preferences and my profile</li>\r\n<li>Possibility to have multiple profiles per user (possibly also profiles that can be controlled by more users in the future)</li>\r\n<li>Private fields</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nSo your existing user field data has disappeared or is about to disappear any moment...','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,5,5,'und',0,'\"More earthy, more casual, less shiny, (less polished).\"\r\nThis would be the direction that I would like to see for the site design, use of color, mood, etc.\r\nSome more structure in columns would be nice too, having some visible or invisible lines that guide the placement of boxes, text etc.\r\nAnd: Content should always have more visual weight than decoration, borders and labels.\r\n\r\nI\'m totally not saying these should be the definitive guidelines for design guys. After all, I am not a designer at all. But as the start of a discussion, I think it\'s ok.\r\n\r\n<blockquote>If a carpet looks too clean and expensive, noone dares to walk on it.</blockquote>\r\nthat was myself, but looks nice as a quote doesn\'t it :)\r\n\r\nExamples:\r\n<a href=\"http://casarobino.org\">Casa Robino</a>\r\nRight amount of casual + earthy. Green is a nice color for a site like this, and it\'s not too much of it. It has a decent structure (sidebar on the right, text aligned in a good way). Headlines get the visual weight they deserve. Horizontal separation lines are placed where necessary, but they are subtle enough to not drain attention.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://couchsurfing.org\">Couchsurfing</a>\r\nEarthy colors, casual look, placement of boxes follows some invisible lines but not too rigid.\r\nMood: The happiness from the picture with the red inflated couch and the profile pics on the front page is far too obtrusive.\r\n\r\nBartik theme (currently active on bw.guaka.org)\r\nIt does not exactly look beautiful, a bit too technical, dull and boring. But at least it\'s not too shiny, not too polished, and has a decent structure of sidebar and text positioning.\r\nProbably we will say goodbye to the blue some day.\r\n\r\nAny thoughts?','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,6,6,'und',0,'I just came across some interesting <a href=\"http://www.istos.it/category/blog-tags/drupal-entities\">blog posts about Entities</a>, a concept new in Drupal 7, which opens up a lot of new possibilities.\r\n\r\nFrom part 2:\r\n<blockquote>\r\nSo the first thing Drupal entities are is means to streamline how we deal with the basic Drupal \"stuff\" of nodes, comments, terms and users.\r\nNow comes the really interesting part to people that don\'t worry so much about how the core of Drupal does things.\r\n\r\n1. You can define your own entities that plug into the whole Drupal way of doing stuff.\r\n2. Any entity can have fields attached to it.\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nAnd something we\'ll want here once it\'s ready:\r\n<blockquote>\r\nThe team over at Examiner.com use entities to store user profile revisioning information (functionality they are hoping to release soon).\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThrough this I also stumbled upon http://drupal.org/project/relation, which is probably useful for implementing friendship links and comments here.\r\n\r\nFinally, the word is out, Drupal 7 will be released on January 5th.  Since many module developers have pledged to have a D7 release of their module we\'ll be able to get a better idea of where we\'re at with this project.','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,7,7,'und',0,'The BW developers mailing list is not working properly now.  I just found Matthias\' post and thought it could be good to take his questions here in the meanwhile.\r\n\r\n<blockquote>I have some questions about the BW-Drupal migration: Will it be possible to port all of the current content from BW to the Drupal based site? Do we need to port everything?</blockquote>\r\n\r\nIt will be possible to migrate all content.  It might have different degrees of difficulties.  Andreas and I have just finished a project to migrate a big .asp site (with a lot of static content in .asp files) and our experience with that will come in pretty handy. We\'ll probably take a different approach, using more widely utilized modules (e.g. <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/tw\">Table Wizard</a> and <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/data\">Data</a>, see also <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/580650\">How Data relates to Table Wizard</a>).\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\nFeatures like trips, blogs or chat are rarely used, but on the other hands\r\nit would not be fair to the users if we delete their content.\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWe should try to migrate everything but if there is only a little bit of content we might have to inform users and ask them about their opinion.  If it\'s really only a little bit of content we could even migrate things manually.\r\n\r\nNote that efforts towards data migration should be delayed until we have a proper proof of concept where the basic functionality is in place.\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\nWhat about translations? There were many people who invested their freetime\r\nto translate the website into many different languages. Their effort\r\nshouldn\'t be in vain.\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nTranslations are essential and we will make a big effort to migrate the results into Drupal - where it makes sense.  Drupal and many often used modules (e.g. Views) are already very well translated and we should try to build with this where it makes sense.  So quite a few translation strings won\'t be migrated since they\'re already available in Drupal.  On the other hand, it will be great to find a way to feed BW translation efforts back into the bigger Drupal ecosphere.\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\nWhere are the biggest challenges in the Drupal migration?\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nI see the biggest challenge in keeping up momentum and finding a way to collaborate.  For example, I had given more people admin rights in order to achieve this but then later realized this is a mistake since it\'s hard to keep track of what\'s going on.  So the first hurdle is to divide the project into chunks that will allow people to work on their preferred parts.  For now this is limited to the theme I think, as long as we\'re with Bartik on this main install the theme is the most harmless part.\r\n','','filtered_html'),('node','page',0,8,8,'und',0,'<h2>The idea</h2> \r\n \r\n<div class=\"subcolumns\"> \r\n  <div class=\"c50l\"> \r\n    <div class=\"subcl\"> \r\n<h3>The concept</h3><p>Imagine arriving in a city like Paris or Mumbai and, instead of trying to find a taxi, there is somebody already waiting for you. Imagine that instead of going to eat at the place recommended by the guidebook, someone shows you their favourite restaurant. Imagine the experience staying as a personal guest of your new friend rather than sleeping in an impersonal hotel room. BeWelcome makes it possible.\r\n    </p><h3>You like the idea? Get active!</h3><p>Join one of our teams: share the work, the commitment and the fun! We are currently looking for:<br />\r\n<h4>People who help building the website</h4><ul><li>software developer (PHP+MySQL)</li><li>web designer ((X)HTML/CSS)</li></ul><br />\r\nGet in contact with <a href=\"members/philipplange\">Philipp</a> or <a href=\"members/fake51\">Peter</a><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>People with writing skills</h4><ul><li> translators (Chinese, Japanese, Arabic, etc)</li></ul><br />\r\nGet in contact with <a href=\"members/sitarane>Julien</a> or <a href=\"members/ieva\">Ieva</a><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>People to promote BeWelcome</h4><h4>Members to start build local communities</h4></p><p>Needs content</p><h3>Your opinion, please!</h3><p>We are constantly working on the improvement of BeWelcome. If you have a suggestion, please <a href=\"http://www.bewelcome.org/forums\">let us know</a>.</p>    </div> \r\n   </div> \r\n \r\n \r\n  <div class=\"c50r\"> \r\n    <div class=\"subcr\"> \r\n<h3>How is it organised?</h3><p>Dreaming alone is not enough. That\'s why we have founded <a href=\"wiki/BeVolunteer\">BeVolunteer</a>, a non-profit organisation registered in Rennes, France. Through BeVolunteer\'s official statutes, we provide a basis for democratic decision making, financial transparency and information security so that we can protect our members and manage the project BeWelcome effectively.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n</p><h3 class=\"first\" ><a href=\"blog/tags/Community News for the frontpage\">Community News</a></h3> \r\n                <div class=\"floatbox\"> \r\n                                            <h4 class=\"news\"><a href=\"blog/sitarane/677\">Servas-BeWelcome update</a></h4> \r\n                        <span class=\"small grey\">written by <a href=\"user/sitarane\">sitarane</a> - 2010/09/30 10:51</span> \r\n                        <p> \r\n                        <p>Monday there was a meeting between the Servas-to-BeWelcome project members. It involved two members of the BW board of directors (including me), one BW coder and three Servas coordinators (including the president of Servas International).<br /><br />The topic was the general roadmap for the project. A draft had been submitted a few days earlier by one Servas coordinator and we were going to discuss it and take it to a complete state. Most of the items of the roadmap were pretty trivial and were quickly agreed upon. However we ran into a disagreement on one point. The draft included the option...</p>                        </p> \r\n                                            <h4 class=\"news\"><a href=\"blog/fake51/626\">BeWelcome server updates</a></h4> \r\n                        <span class=\"small grey\">written by <a href=\"user/fake51\">fake51</a> - 2010/01/30 18:33</span> \r\n                        <p> \r\n                        It\'s been stated a couple of times on the forum and possibly written about in some forum posts: BeWelcome is relocating it\'s test server to one of it\'s members (Tobixen - many thanks!). In connection with this, you might experience some problems if you try to reach the old BV wiki or the trac pages (if you\'re trying to put in a bug report). Things should be up and running within a day or two again, though - so please, don\'t worry too much if you see some pages broken, they should be fixed again soon.                        </p> \r\n                    \r\n                    <a href=\"blog/tags/Community News for the frontpage\">Read more</a> \r\n    </div> \r\n  </div> ','','full_html'),('node','blog',0,9,9,'und',0,'See <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/1007286\">og.module on D7 - how to join a group?</a> on drupal.org\r\n\r\n<blockquote>I should add it to the README, but should find the time for it, or If you guys feel like writing a small patch...\r\n\r\nIn short -- enable og-ui module, and in your content type go to \"display fields\" and in the group field select \"Group subscription\" as the formatter.</blockquote>\r\n\r\nDid that. Now everyone except the group author can subscribe or unsubscribe.\r\n\r\nIs this enough for us?\r\nSee <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/1006348\">Make group memberships fieldable.</a> on drupal.org\r\n\r\n<blockquote>I\'m not very clear on the issue. Currently there is a single field that is responsible for subscription, which uses field API. This field\'s name is hardcoded and is important, so we can keep track using this name what entity/ bundle is a group or a group post.</blockquote>','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,10,10,'und',0,'I set up a <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/views\">View</a> to <a href=\"/list-members\">list all members</a> - not that we have so many here, but I thought it was nice to fill in some menu links quickly.\r\n\r\nWhen I wanted to increase the number of items shown on the first page I ran into an issue.  I <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/994856\">copied the error into a d.o bug report for Views</a>.  Within 6 hours dereine replied that he had committed a fix (to cvs).\r\n\r\nI don\'t like CVS so I decided to wait for <a href=\"http://drupal.org/\">d.o</a> to come up with a new Views 7.x-3.x-dev package and today I fetched that (with <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/drush\">drush dl</a>, since drush up is not working properly on this install now).  Problem solved - for us and also for the 100000s of other websites that will be using D7 Views.','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,11,11,'und',0,'I drush upped.  Which means I upgraded all modules and core to Drupal 7.0-rc4.  I also found that og has an alpha release now for D7, so I drush dl\'d that.\r\n\r\nIf you haven\'t tried drush yet: go get it, it\'s awesome.  It\'s a <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/drush\">DRUpal SHell</a>, which means you get tons of power at your fingertips, saving you hours of time fetching modules, clearing cache, running cron, going into a Drupal database, executing PHP stuff from a Drupal site environment and much more.','','filtered_html'),('node','page',0,12,12,'und',0,'This Drupal installation is an attempt at moving BeWelcome to Drupal.  You can sign up here and help out with the creation and migration process.  You will also find regular updates here about our progress. Check and edit <a href=\"http://couchwiki.org/en/Migrating_BeWelcome_to_Drupal\">this page on Couchwiki for a messy overview of the migration</a>.  We\'re also posting blog posts with mostly technical status updates and discussions.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>This is not the most recent version of BW Drupal. Check http://gitorious.org/bw-drupal for that</em></strong>','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,13,13,'und',0,'Sitting in our living room in Brussels with <a href=\"http://benn.org/\">Meinhard</a> and <a href=\"http://triphopping.com/\">Kenny</a>.  Hopefully good stuff will come out :)\r\n\r\nI\'ll be updating this post as we go.\r\n\r\nSome past activity:\r\n- Friday evening Meinhard managed to set up BW on Drupal during the train ride from Hamburg.\r\n- Thursday night Kenny got an introduction to Drupal and is very interested in migrating Triphopping to Drupal.\r\n- https://gitorious.org/bw-drupal\r\n- think about what to do at http://www.bewelcome.org/wiki/Berlin_summer_camp\r\n\r\n<h2>General issues</h2>\r\nSome problems we see with current BeWelcome:\r\n- login? easy login => openid (also allows for google and yahoo openid)\r\n- usability\r\n-- forum is a mess usability-wise\r\n-- profiles (profile pic should open bigger pic, not gallery with smaller pic, \"difficult to upload pics\")\r\n\r\n<h2>what needs to be migrated?</h2>\r\n','','filtered_html'),('node','page',0,14,14,'und',0,'<h4>1. Registration</h4> \r\n<p>By registering with BeWelcome and creating your profile, you agree to provide accurate, up-to-date and complete information about yourself. You further agree that you will ensure that this information is kept accurate and up to date at all times. This is especially important with respect to your email address, since that is the primary way in which we will communicate with you about your account. If you fail to follow this rule, we reserve the right to edit, close and/or delete your account and profile and thereby remove any information and prevent you from using the site.\r\nAs part of the registration process, you will designate a password, subject to our password security requirements. It is your responsibility to keep this password confidential. If you find out that your password or account is being used by someone without your consent, or you discover any other breach of security, you agree to notify us promptly without delay.</p> \r\n \r\n<h4>2. Privacy</h4> \r\n<p>We are committed to safeguarding your privacy. Thus we understand your wish and respect your right to privacy and personal information. However, by submitting your photograph and any other personal information, you allow any member of BeWelcome to view and use this information. If you do not wish to keep your personal picture or information private vis-&agrave;-vis other members of BeWelcome, you shall choose to hide it accordingly. We reserve the right to collect further personal information from you that we do not post on BeWelcome. Under normal circumstances we will not transfer your personal information to unaffiliated third parties without your consent. However, we reserve the right to transfer such information without your consent in the following cases: to prevent an emergency, to protect or enforce our legal rights, to protect or enforce legal rights of a third party or in pursuance to a court order or subpoena or as otherwise required or permitted by law. This also applies to messages you send through BeWelcome. While these messages are normally only read by respective senders and addressees, you agree to disclose those messages to volunteers for spam monitoring. BeVolunteer may use the email address you provided upon registration in order to send you regular newsletters, which, however, you can unsubscribe from. You further agree to your visits of other members profiles being logged and displayed to them or logged for administrative or technical purposes.</p> \r\n \r\n<h4>3. Liability</h4> \r\n<p>We offer a platform for registered members to arrange hospitality exchange and to use tools to plan and record their travels. Even though we hope to meet your requirements, we do not warrant any information provided on the site to be accurate and reliable at any relevant time, to meet your expectations, to offer error-free, uninterrupted and fast service. We shall not be responsible or liable in case of a dispute with one of our members. You thus exempt us herewith from any claims or liabilities whatsoever arising from or in connection with our service. This Service is provided by BeWelcome and BeVolunteer, the organization behind BeWelcome (registrated in France at \'la pr&eacute;fecture de Rennes\' with the number W3530003536) on an &quot;AS-IS&quot; and &quot;AS AVAILABLE&quot; basis and BeVolunteer reserves the right to modify, suspend or discontinue the Service, in its sole discretion, at any time and without notice. You agree that BeVolunteer is not and will not be liable to you for any modification, suspension or discontinuance of the Service.</p> \r\n \r\n<h4>4. General Conduct</h4> \r\n<p>You agree that you shall not</p> \r\n<ul> \r\n  <li>(a) interfere with or disrupt (or attempt to interfere with or disrupt) this Service or servers, through, including, but not limited to, the use of viruses, cancel bots, Trojan horses, harmful code, flood pings, denial-of-service attacks, packet or IP spoofing, forged routing or electronic mail address information or similar methods or technology</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(b) provide any information to BeWelcome that is false or misleading, that would otherwise hide your identity or that you do not have the right to disclose</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(c) violate any applicable law or regulation. Since BeVolunteer (the legal organization behind BeWelcome) is registrated in France at \'la pr&eacute;fecture de Rennes\' (number W3530003536), French law is applicable</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(d) violate the rights of any third party, including, but not limited to, intellectual property, privacy, publicity or contractual rights</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(e) collect, store or abuse any information you obtain through our Service including any information about any other user for any unauthorized purposes</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(f) use our Services to transmit, distribute, post or submit any information concerning any other person or entity, including, but not limited to, personal contact information or credit, debit, calling card or account numbers</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(g) molest, \"stalk\" or harass any other user of our Services</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(h) use our Services for any commercial purpose especially in connection with the distribution of unsolicited commercial email (&quot;Spam&quot;) or advertisements</li> \r\n \r\n  <li>(i) assist any third party in doing any of the foregoing</li> \r\n</ul> \r\n \r\n<p>You agree to defend, indemnify, and hold harmless BeWelcome and BeVolunteer, its directors and volunteers, from and against any claims, liabilities, damages, losses, and expenses, including, but not limited to, reasonable legal and expert fees, arising out of or in any way connected with your access to or use of the Services, or your violation of these Terms.</p> \r\n \r\n<h4>5. Content</h4> \r\n<p>You are responsible for all the Content you upload, download, and otherwise copy, distribute and display using the Service. You must have the legal right to copy, distribute and display all parts of any content that you upload, download and otherwise copy, distribute and display. Content provided to you by others, or made available through websites, magazines, books and other sources, may be protected by copyright and should not be uploaded, downloaded, or otherwise copied, distributed or displayed without the consent of the copyright owner or as otherwise permitted by law.</p> \r\n \r\n<p>You agree that you shall not post or submit any content that</p> \r\n<ul> \r\n  <li>(a) is libelous</li> \r\n  <li>(b) contains nudity, pornography, pedophile or sexually explicit content</li> \r\n  <li>(c) is in any way discriminating against ethnic, racial, sexual or religious groups by stereotypical depiction or otherwise</li> \r\n  <li>(d) contains offensive language or images</li> \r\n  <li>(e) glorifies violence and the use of drugs or characterize either as acceptable or desirable</li> \r\n</ul> \r\n \r\n<h4>6. General</h4> \r\n<p>These Terms constitute the entire agreement between BeWelcome and the legal organization behind it, BeVolunteer, and you with respect to your use of the Service. BeWelcome\'s or BeVolunteer\'s failure to enforce any right or provision in these Terms shall not constitute a waiver of such right or provision. If a court should find that one or more provisions contained in these Terms is invalid, you agree that the remainder of the Terms shall be enforceable. These Terms shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of France. Any disputes arising under or in connection with these Terms shall be subject to the exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of France. BeVolunteer reserves the right to amend these terms as seen appropriate without prior notice.</p> ','','full_html'),('node','blog',0,15,15,'und',0,'Not long ago I had to migrate a bunch of Drupal nodes from a test site to a live site. This situation is not the same as ours, because our original content does not live in Drupal, and I was on D6. Still, there are some things we can learn from:\r\n1. Structure and completeness of imported content for whatever API functions we use.\r\n2. Foreign keys, and the inevitable mismatch of auto-increment ids.\r\n\r\n1. Structure and completeness of imported content.\r\nDrupal\'s node_save() or entity_save() API. This API (in D6), has some expectations on the format and completeness of data (usually nested structures of associative array and vanilla stdClass objects) we want to import. If something is not working as expected, this is a place to look.\r\n\r\n2. Foreign keys.\r\nA lot of the relations between db tables on bw-rox site will translate into relations and references between Drupal objects. The structure will be different, and auto-increment ids will be different.\r\nIf a user location on bw-rox has a country id of 26, the same country might have an id of 111 on bw-drupal. Or it might even be a string key instead of an auto-increment id.\r\n\r\nSolution: Maintain a map of primary keys.\r\nFor each imported piece of content, we should therefore maintain a reference to the original bw-rox object. This can be stored in an integer-valued field, or in a custom table that we have to keep up to date.\r\nWe then will use that map to alter the foreign key values on imported content.\r\nWe need to be careful with the order of things we import.\r\nIn some cases there might be circular dependencies, so we have to keep a list of postponed foreign key updates that have to be done later.\r\n\r\nIf we use existing solutions for the data migration, we need to find out if they are flexible enough to deal with these issues. Probably we will have to write some code of our own to hook into the import module. At that time I used <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/node_export\">Node export</a>, which does have a nice API for exactly this purpose, but as said, this does only work from Drupal to Drupal.','','filtered_html'),('node','blog',0,16,16,'und',0,'I de-adminned everyone except user 1, myself and lemon-head.  D7 is still a bit too volatile - and you don\'t need admin rights to play with it.  Instead, it\'s easy to set up your own Drupal 7 installation and e.g. create a first BW theme for D7. \r\n\r\nIf wanted I can make the Features available that I\'ve created so far: BW user profile, BW FAQ and BW wiki.  The first is the most interesting, but right now it\'s not yet possible to export the complete user field settings, only the individual fields can be exported.  BW FAQ is a little attempt at the BW\'s FAQ, and BW wiki likewise for the wiki.\r\n\r\nThere\'s also a trusted role, which can easily be given some more permissions if needed.  And I had forgotten to turn on the View user profiles permission to authenticated users.  That\'s fixed now, so it\'s already a bit more interesting.','','filtered_html'),('node','page',0,17,17,'und',0,'Privacy Policy\r\nBeWelcome offers an online place to meet friends, and a chance to meet people in the real world. This Privacy Policy is intended to inform you of BeWelcome\'s policies and practices regarding the collection, use and disclosure of any Personal Information 